     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">Output 3: SUPPORTING MULTISECTORAL COORDINATION AND INCLUSIVE RESPONSES                             Indicators/ Baseline/Target
1. No of states studied for sectoral social and economic impact assessment.
BASELINE- 0; TARGET - 6 states
Gender Marker- 2</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">UNDP India undertook a panel study of migrants in India to understand the (short term) impact of the lockdown and its (medium term) implications along with recovery patterns. Independent agencies were commissioned to collect data from 6 states for two time periods &#x2013; May-June, 2020 for the baseline assessment and December, 2020 for the medium term assessment. Internally developed questionnaires were deployed that captured data on characteristics, impact of lockdown, health, social protection, monthly incomes, meal consumption, working conditions among other themes. 
&#x2022;	The results indicate that while the lockdown had a devastating impact on the migrant sample in terms of employment, wages and food consumption, recovery trends are visible across these domains in the medium run. 
&#x2022;	A majority of the sample received provision of ration and pulses which helped them survive during the lockdown. 
&#x2022;	The results also indicate a reversal in migration tendencies with preference for local jobs and skilling. 
&#x2022;	From a policy perspective, the findings call for an expansion of social security welfare nets, investments in local jobs providing platforms such as the MGNREGA and a greater focus on the recovery of the disproportionately affected women migrants.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
